<br>
___<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1366</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The Eucharist is thus a sacrifice because it re-presents (makes present) the sacrifice of the cross, because it is its memorial and because it applies its fruit: <br>
<br>
[Christ], our Lord and God, was once and for all to offer himself to God the Father by his death on the altar of the cross, to accomplish there an everlasting redemption. But because his priesthood was not to end with his death, at the Last Supper &quot;on the night when he was betrayed,&quot; [he wanted] to leave to his beloved spouse the Church a visible sacrifice (as the nature of man demands) by which the bloody sacrifice which he was to accomplish once for all on the cross would be re-presented, its memory perpetuated until the end of the world, and its salutary power be applied to the forgiveness of the sins we daily commit.187 <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1367</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The sacrifice of Christ and the sacrifice of the Eucharist are one single sacrifice: &quot;The victim is one and the same: the same now offers through the ministry of priests, who then offered himself on the cross; only the manner of offering is different.&quot; &quot;And since in this divine sacrifice which is celebrated in the Mass, the same Christ who offered himself once in a bloody manner on the altar of the cross is contained and is offered in an unbloody manner. . . this sacrifice is truly propitiatory.&quot;188 </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
___<br>
<br>
Unless of course I missed the point of the contention? <p>“How can you claim to love a God you can’t see if you fail to love the brother or sister standing right in front of you?” – Mother Theresa</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=t0mmyt>T0mmyT</A> at: 12/3/03 11:41 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 667<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/3/03 12:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=28>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: sacrifice</span><hr size=1> Nah, I don't think you've missed the point.  I think the contention comes from the fact that &quot;the same now offers through the ministry of priests&quot;.<br>
<br>
Even though it is an unbloody act there is still the concept of a sacrifice involved and some find that - for lack of a better word - unpalatable.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think of the order of the mass and the fact that what we offer is the bread and wine which then becomes the flesh and blood.<br>
<br>
Maybe it's terminology, but I can appreciate the reservations some Christians have about this aspect of Catholicism.  At the same time, I firmly believe in the presence of the body and blood in the Eucharistic celebration.  It (to me) is not only a symbolic commemorative.  However, as to the exact nature (transubstantiation, consubstantiation or Holy mystery)... well, I can appreciate where there is some debate on the issue. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://groups.msn.com/_Secure/0UQDZAvEZO00g9M*!6iyVLQ09mpS*ZPd2Rp6ZIWzqL0ujzIKF8WCuVoelKGqy05gAMAtOV9Uw8pItiRYCdYaZJ4Rc!MhNSPhku9uuiQ0MXtbEJEQIkD*SMdrxtatntdkK/flag_cdn.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filosofer>filosofer</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=green><b>Wise Cleric<br>of The Hearth</b></font></span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/3/03 8:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: sacrifice</span><hr size=1> Thanks, TOmmy and esdras for the clarifications on the RCC position. The variation in the RCC authors can cause problems because some of them receive the imprintaur (officially approved as in agreement with RCC doctrine)and others do not.<br>
<br>
I think the biggest difference regarding what happens in the Lord's Supper is that the RCC teaches (as noted above) that this is a sacrifice (hence, Law = something the person does), because the grace makes the person worthy to be forgiven, whereas Lutherans would say that it is sacrament meaning that the person is forgiven not because of being worthy, but because of what Christ has done for the person (Gospel = something that God does). <br>
<br>
Obviously we can see that there are definition problems, partly because Lutherans and RCC define &quot;sacrament&quot; differently. (BTW, I would partially agree with the Orthodox statement about  &quot;it's a mystery&quot; since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>sacramentum</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in Latin means &quot;mystery.&quot;) For Lutherans, we define a sacrament as having three parts:<br>
<br>
1. Instituted by Christ<br>
<br>
2. For the forgiveness of sins<br>
<br>
3. Visible element(s)<br>
<br>
According to this definition, only Baptism (Matthew 28:18-20;  Acts 2:38-39; 1 Peter 3:21; Romans 6:1-5) and the Lord's Supper (Matthew 26:26-28 and parallels; 1 Corinthians 10:16-17 and 11:23-30) would be considered sacraments (means of grace). (Sometimes you might hear/read about the &quot;1/2 sacrament&quot; - namely, Confession/Absolution, but it lacks the visible sign.<br>
<br>
RCC doctrine provides a different definition, and thus ends up with seven sacraments: Baptism, Confirmation, Lord's Supper, marriage, holy orders, penance, extreme unction/last rites. <p>In Christ,<br>
<br>
filo<br>
<br>
For I decided to know nothing among you except Jesus Christ and him crucified.<br>
<br>
1 Corinthians 2:2</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 671<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/4/03 9:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=30>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: sacrifice</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the biggest difference regarding what happens in the Lord's Supper is that the RCC teaches (as noted above) that this is a sacrifice (hence, Law = something the person does), because the grace makes the person worthy to be forgiven, whereas Lutherans would say that it is sacrament meaning that the person is forgiven not because of being worthy, but because of what Christ has done for the person (Gospel = something that God does).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think that even though the priest during the Mass goes through the actions of the sacrifice - the grace is still all from God.<br>
<br>
Additionally, what we offer (or sacrifice) at the Mass is the bread and the wine (fruit of the vine and work of human hands).  Additionally, when we say what we have to offer, we begin with, &quot;Blessed are you, Lord, God of all creation. Through your goodness we have this (bread/wine) to offer.  Even our offering is becuase of God.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, the bread and wine becomes the body and blood through the power of the Holy Spirit, as the priest says, &quot;Lord, you are holy indeed, the fountain of all holiness. Let your Spirit come upon these gifts to make them holy, so that they may become for us the body and blood of our Lord, Jesus Christ.&quot;<br>
<br>
We also reaffirm that we are not worthy to receive the body and blood or be forgiven.  Before receiving communion the congregation says what is, in my opinion, one of the most important statements uttered by the participants of a Mass...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Lord, I am not worthy to receive you, but only say the word and I shall be healed.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
That is said just before we go to receive communion.<br>
<br>
So while there is an offering/sacrifice presented during the Mass, I never really see that as the focal point.  That one line I quoted above and then receiving the body and blood is the most glorious part of the Mass.  And at that time, the focus is not on ourselves, but on God, Jesus Christ and the grace and sacrifice given to us, even though not one of us is worthy to receive the gift.<br>
<br>
 <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
